<span id="xv.iv.iv.cx"></span>

<span id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p1"></span> <span class="c4"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p1.1"></span>Canon CIX.  (Greek cxij. continued.)</span>

<span id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p2"></span>That Adam was not created by God
subject to death.

<span id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p3"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p3.1"></span>That</span> whosoever says that Adam, the
first man, was created mortal, so that whether he had sinned or not, he
would have died in body—that is, he would have gone forth of the body,
not because his sin merited this, but by natural necessity, let him be
anathema.

<span id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p4"></span><span class="c4"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p4.1"></span>Notes.</span>

<span id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p5"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p5.1"></span>Ancient Epitome of Canon CIX.</span>

<span id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p6"></span>Whoso shall assert that the protoplast
would have died without sin and through natural necessity, let him be
anathema.

<span id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p7"></span>Canon CVIII. is the introduction to the
Synod of Carthage of May 1, <span class="sc"><span
id="xv.iv.iv.cx-p7.1"></span>a.d.</span> 418; and Canon CIX. is Canon j.
of that synod.

